Pour the @water{300%ml} for the rice into a #medium saucepan{} with a tight-fitting #lid{}.

Stir in the @Jasmine Rice{150%g} and @salt{1/4%tsp} and bring to the boil. Once boiling, turn the heat down to medium and cover with the lid.

Leave to cook for ~{10%minutes}, then remove the pan from the heat (still covered) and leave to the side for another ~{10%minutes} or until ready to serve (the rice will continue to cook in its own steam).

Meanwhile, trim the @Cucumber{1/2}, then quarter lengthways. Chop widthways into small pieces. Peel and grate the @Ginger{1/2}.

Peel and grate the @Garlic Clove{1} (or use a #garlic press{}).

Pick the @Mint{1} leaves from their stalks (discard the stalks). Zest and halve the @Lime{1/2}.

Crush the @Salted Peanuts{25%g} in the unopened sachet using a #rolling pin{}.

Heat a #large frying pan{} on high heat (no oil).

Once hot, add the @British Beef Mince{240%g} and fry until browned, ~{4-5%minutes}. Use a #spoon{} to break it up as it cooks, then drain and discard any excess fat.

> IMPORTANT: Wash your hands and equipment after handling raw mince.

Stir in the @Thai Style Spice Mix{1} (add less if you'd prefer things milder), ginger and garlic. Cook for ~{1-2%minutes}.

Add the @Ketjap Manis{25%ml} and a splash of water, then stir and simmer until glazed, ~{1%minute}. Once cooked, cover with a lid to keep warm.

> IMPORTANT: The mince is cooked when no longer pink in the middle.

Meanwhile, mix the @Soy Sauce{25%ml}, @Sugar{1} and lime juice together in a #large bowl{}. Set aside.

Pop the cucumber and mint leaves into the dressing bowl. Toss to coat.

Reheat the mince if needed.

Fluff up your rice with a #fork{}, then stir through the lime zest and share between your bowls.

Top with the beef mince and sprinkle the peanuts over the top. Serve with the cucumber salad alongside.

> TIP: Load your fork with a bit of everything for the best experience! Enjoy!

> If you've chosen to get beef mince instead of pork, cook the recipe in the same way.